Formatting Text: Used to clean and standardize text data for better analysis
Why Format Text?
 Ensure consistency in spelling and structure.
 Make your data clean and ready for visuals or analysis.
 Fix common data entry issues like extra spaces, wrong case, inconsistent symbols.
To Format Text: Power Query Editor → Transform tab → Format dropdown
Text Formatting Options
1. UPPERCASE
 Converts all letters to CAPITALS.
 Good for standardizing codes, names, etc.
Example: "bangalore" → "BANGALORE"
2. lowercase
 Converts all letters to small case.
Example: "DATA SCIENCE" → "data science"
3. Capitalize Each Word
 Makes the first letter of each word uppercase, rest lowercase.
Example: "data analyst" → "Data Analyst"
Use Case: Formatting names, cities, titles.
4. Trim
 Removes extra spaces from the beginning and end of text.
Example: " John " → "John"
Use Case: Clean up manual entries or copied data.
5. Clean
 Removes non-printable characters (e.g., invisible symbols copied from web or PDFs).
Example: "Hello World" (with hidden character) → "Hello World"
6. Add Prefix / Add Suffix
 Adds text before (prefix) or after (suffix) each value.
Example – Add Prefix: Original: "123" → With prefix "ID-" → "ID-123"
Example – Add Suffix: Original: "Bangalore" → With suffix " City" → "Bangalore City"
