Time-Based Operations:
Path:
Transform tab → Select a time column → Click on Time Add Column tab → Time

1. Time Only
Purpose: Extracts only the time part from a datetime value. Use case: You want to remove the date and just keep values like 08:30:00. Example: 2024-05-01 08:30:00 → 08:30:00

2. Local Time
Purpose: Converts a datetime value into the local system time zone. Use case: Working with data from different time zones and want to align all to your local time. Example: UTC 03:00 → adjusted to local time zone (e.g., +05:30)

3. Parse
Purpose: Converts a text string that looks like a time into an actual time data type. Use case: When your time column is in text format like "14:45" and you want to use time functions. Example: "14:45" (Text) → 14:45:00 (Time)

4. Hour → From/Start of/End of
Purpose: Extracts hour part or rounds time to start/end of the hour.
 Hour → From: Pulls just the hour (e.g., 14:30:00 → 14)
 Start of Hour: Rounds down to 14:00:00
 End of Hour: Rounds up to 14:59:59

5. Minute
Purpose: Extracts the minute component from a time value. Example: 14:45:30 → 45


6. Second
Purpose: Extracts the second part from a time value. Example: 14:45:30 → 30

7. Subtract
Purpose: Subtracts one time value from another. Returns a duration. Use case: Calculate time differences (e.g., working hours) Example: Logout - Login = Duration (02:15:00)

8. Combine Date and Time
Purpose: Combines two separate columns — one with date, one with time — into a single datetime column. Example:
 Date: 2025-06-12
 Time: 14:00:00
 Combined: 2025-06-12 14:00:00

9. Earliest
Purpose: Returns the earliest (minimum) time from the selected column. Use case: Identify first log-in, start time, etc.

10. Latest
Purpose: Returns the latest (maximum) time value. Use case: Find the last log-out or latest transaction.
